issue.title: Add aircraft ground position decoding on 1090MHz
issue.body:
Currently, ADSBee only decodes airborne positions for aircraft. It would be good to also report aircraft on the ground along with their associated positions.

This will require a [slightly different CPR decoding implementation](https://mode-s.org/1090mhz/content/ads-b/4-surface-position.html) with a different global grid, as well as a reference position. The reference position could be pulled from some sort of averaged position across multiple airborne aircraft contacts, or from a position that can be input by the user.

comment.body:
> This will require a [slightly different CPR decoding implementation](https://mode-s.org/1090mhz/content/ads-b/4-surface-position.html) with a different global grid, as well as a reference position. The reference position could be pulled from some sort of averaged position across multiple airborne aircraft contacts, or from a position that can be input by the user.

If I read this correctly, the reference position can be the position of the receiver which is easy in case a GPS is attached. `readsb` has obviously implemented the CPR surface decoding here: [decodeCPRsurface](https://github.com/wiedehopf/readsb/blob/539e11d463153b08378c84cd5f5c8394592c9871/cpr.c#L223)

issue.title: simplify regexp/grep syntax
issue.body:
This commit cleans up the regexp/grep syntax by isolating the regexp pattern and glob syntax to search expressions and using conventional strings for the functions regexp(), regexp_replace(), and grep().  This allowed us to remove a bunch of special case syntax for these functions from the PEG grammar.

This change means that globbing is no longer available for grep, which now uses only regular expressions.  If we want to allow globbing, we can enable that with a function that converts glob strings to regexps or perhaps introduce a g"glob" style string.

We also removed the implied "this" argument from grep and now require two arguments.

Detailed docs updates are forthcoming in the book branch.

review.body: ### Review Summary REQUEST_CHANGES Thank you for your hard work—your project is very close! However, there are a few **critical blockers** that must be addressed before approval: 1. **Direct Model Reference Instead of get_user_model()** - In `taxi/forms.py`, the Meta classes for `DriverCreationForm` and `DriverLicenseUpdateForm` reference `Driver` directly. The requirement is to use `get_user_model()` instead. This ensures flexibility if the user model changes and is a core Django best practice. - **How to fix:** Replace: ```python class Meta: model = Driver ``` with: ```python from django.contrib.auth import get_user_model class Meta: model = get_user_model() ``` 2. **Missing Trailing Slashes in URLs** - In `taxi/urls.py`, several URL patterns are missing the required trailing slash (`/`). This is an explicit requirement and can cause routing issues in Django. - **How to fix:** Ensure all URL patterns end with a `/`, for example: ```python path('driver/update//', ...) path('driver/delete//', ...) path('cars//assign/', ...) path('cars//remove/', ...) ``` (Double-check all patterns for compliance.) 3. **Missing 'Cancel' Button on Delete Confirmation Page** - In `templates/taxi/driver_confirm_delete.html`, only a 'Delete' button is present. The checklist requires both a 'Delete' and a 'Cancel' button, with 'Cancel' returning the user to the previous or a safe page (like the driver list or detail page). - **How to fix:** Add a 'Cancel' button, for example: ```html Cancel ``` Or use JavaScript to go back to the previous page if preferred. 4. **View Naming Consistency** - The update view for Driver is named `DriverUpdateForm` instead of the conventional `DriverUpdateView`. While this may not break functionality, it can cause confusion and is referenced in the requirements for consistent naming. - **How to fix:** Rename the class to `DriverUpdateView` in both `views.py` and all references (including `urls.py`). --- Once you address these blockers, your project will be fully compliant and ready for approval! comment.body:
The zoom logic appears inverted. When distance is greater than the threshold (user is far), it keeps the current zoom level, but when distance is less than the threshold (user is close), it uses Math.Max which could zoom out instead of in. This contradicts the typical expectation that being close should result in higher zoom levels.
```suggestion
        var targetZoomLevel = distance > closeDistanceThresholdKM ? currentZoomLevel : CLOSE_ZOOM_LEVEL;
```

comment.body: Do we really want these to be generated though?  The perspective I approached this from was to treat the `ScriptEntry` labels and matching header values not as constants, but instead as though they were effectively equivalent to functions that can be externally called, just in a .s file instead of in a .c file.  With that in mind, manually maintaining the function/label definitions in a matching .h file, instead of generating them, becomes the intuitive approach.

review.body: ## Pull Request Overview This PR introduces dynamic zoom level adjustment based on distance thresholds when the location button is clicked. The changes replace a fixed distance threshold with a calculated one that varies based on the current zoom level, providing more adaptive map behavior. - Adds a new method to calculate distance thresholds dynamically based on zoom level - Updates the location button click logic to use the dynamic threshold instead of a fixed constant - Modifies zoom level determination to be more context-aware of the current map state --- **Tip:** Customize your code reviews with copilot-instructions.md.
